# data-models-relationships

## Core Data Models

### Organization Hierarchy
- Multi-tenant organization structure with inheritance patterns
- Organization admins have full visibility across member contexts
- Members inherit organization-level settings but can override locally
- Organization-specific knowledge bases with granular access controls
Importance Score: 90

### User Context Model
- Hierarchical user context system with bidirectional sync
- Personal workspace vs organizational member contexts
- Sales objectives and preferences stored at user level
- Context inheritance rules from organization to user level
Importance Score: 85

### CRM Integration Models
- Dual-level CRM token storage (org-wide and user-specific)
- Contact/Lead matching algorithms with fallback strategies
- Relationship history tracking with temporal context
- Cross-platform synchronization rules
Importance Score: 85

### Document/Knowledge Model
- Organization-scoped document repositories
- Hierarchical permission system for material access
- Material categorization and ownership tracking
- Version control for shared sales content
Importance Score: 75

## Key Relationships

1. Organization -> Users
- One-to-many relationship with role inheritance
- Admin privileges propagate through hierarchy
- Context sharing rules based on organizational role
- Member activity tracking within org scope

2. Users -> CRM Integrations
- Individual users can connect multiple CRM instances
- Organization-wide CRM connections available to all members
- Relationship data syncs based on user's org role
- Permission inheritance for CRM access

3. Organizations -> Knowledge Base
- Organization-owned document repositories
- Granular sharing controls at document level
- Role-based access inheritance
- Cross-organization isolation enforcement

## Integration Points
- Salesforce contact/lead synchronization
- LinkedIn profile data extraction
- Email provider connections (Gmail/Outlook)
- Calendar integration for contact tracking

